\item LLMRank 
also performs poorly.
Solely relying on the LLM's latent knowledge about books is not sufficient
when coping with long-tail items.
Popularity and position bias [hou2023large] further aggravate this adverse effect.
To mitigate position bias,
we ran a variant with smaller test sets of only 20 candidate {negative} items (per positive test item), as in the original setup of [hou2023large].
This boosts the NDCG@5 for LLMRank from 4.8% to 23.5%, on GR-1k-rich in standard evaluation, which is still a large margin below CUP{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0027||FO}} reaching 38.3% (and similarly big gaps for the other dataset). 
\item Between the three CUP configurations, we see a clear trend: 
review-based user profiling ({{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0028||FO}}) outperforms user profiles based on genres or categories ({{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0029||FO}}), and simplifying item-side text to titles and tags alone by removing item description ({{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0030||FO}}) performs worst.
Remarkably, even CUP{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0031||FO}} is better than all the baselines. CUP{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0032||FO}} is ca. 5 percentage points better in NDCG@5 than the baselines.
\item In search-based evaluation 
(Table (ref)), 
the absolute results are much lower, emphasizing the difficulty of this realistic mode. Still, the relative comparisons between methods are nearly identical to the results with standard evaluation. 
Again, CUP{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0033||FO}} is the winner, with a clear margin.
\item The absolute numbers on GR-1K-rich are generally higher, due to the different
data characteristics. The gains by CUP{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0034||FO}} over the baselines and
over the simpler CUP configurations are even more pronounced
(e.g., outperforming BENEFICT{{arxiv_2311_01314_FO0035||FO}} by 8 percentage points with
standard evaluation).
